{"type":"message","id":"3744a69b","parentId":"fff2bac4","timestamp":"2026-04-21T04:50:37.990Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The gateway is running (multiple processes) but not listening on port 18789. There's something fundamentally wrong with the gateway startup. \n\nLet me think about this differently. The fact that `openclaw gateway start` exits with no output might mean it's running as a daemon and immediately returning. But then the processes we see might be the daemonized gateway processes.\n\nBut if the daemonized gateway processes are running, why aren't they listening on port 18789?\n\nWait, I just realized something. Looking at the config again:\n```json\n\"gateway\": {\n    \"mode\": \"local\",\n    \"port\": 18789,\n\n\n```\n\nThe `bind: \"loopback\"` setting might be the culprit here. Maybe in this version of OpenClaw, `\"loopback\"` doesn't resolve to `127.0.0.1` properly, so the binding fails silently. Let me try changing it to explicitly bind to `127.0.0.1` instead.\n\nActually, wait. The old gateway from April 2 was running fine and listening on that same port, so this config should work. The issue might be with how the new VPS is handling the network binding.\n\nLet me reconsider this from scratch. I need to check if something else is already listening on port 18789, verify the config file is actually being read correctly, and see if the gateway has permission to bind to that port at all.\n\n```\nActually, I'm wondering if the real problem is that the config file specifies `\"bind\": \"loopback\"` but the system doesn't have loopback properly configured, or there's a conflict with how the daemon is interpreting the binding address.\n```\n\nLet me try switching to `\"bind\": \"0.0.0.0\"` instead to see if that resolves the issue. I should also check if the old VPS has any insights about how the gateway was originally configured to start.","thinkingSignature":"b62631b4b72791dd20c270f7d2ec796e6e2031d1aa52c1df